nts":[{"name":"Erlandsen","meanings":["Norwegian and Danish: patronymic from the personal name <i>Erland</i> (see   Erlandson  )."]},{"name":"Erland","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Obert.","Norwegian: habitational name from a farm in southwestern Norway so named, from Old Norse <i>elri</i> ‘alder’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’, ‘farm’.","Probably also an American shortened form of Swedish <b>Erlandsson</b> (see   Erlandson  )."]}]},{"name":"Kagg","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Kent): nickname from an unrecorded Middle English <i>fag</i>, perhaps a side-form of Middle English <i>fagge</i> (Old English <i>facg</i>), which is attested only as a name for a species of flat fish but possibly had a general sense ‘(someone or something) disproportionately broad or wide’, and which may survive in 19th-century northern English dialect <i>fadge</i> ‘a short, thickset person’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Matts","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Matthew</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Matthew","meanings":["form of the name of the Christian evangelist, author of the first gospel in the New Testament. His name is a form of the Hebrew name <i>Mattathia</i>, meaning ‘gift of God’, which is fairly common in the Old Testament, being rendered in the Authorized Version in a number of different forms: <i>Mattan(i)ah</i>, <i>Mattatha(h)</i>, <i>Mattithiah</i>, <i>Mattathias</i>, and so on. In the Authorized Version, the evangelist is regularly referred to as <i>Matthew</i>, while the apostle chosen to replace Judas Iscariot is distinguished as   Matthias .  A related name from the same Hebrew roots, but reversed, is   Jonathan .  Throughout the English-speaking world <i>Matthew</i> has been particularly popular since the 1970s."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1702076,"age":71,"year":"1436","